Well, first I saw what the maximum possible payout for a round could be listed in the instructions, which was $1 if everyone guesses 100, so I tried guessing 100 hoping the other person would have seen that and also guessed 100.    After I saw that that worked I decided to keep doing it as long as it did work, and it continued to until the end, so I chose 100 every time.

I started with modestly low guesses, as those seemed to be more likely to be close to correct. The initial instructions mentioned examples that were relatively low, so I thought other people would be most likely to be primed by those numbers, and I guessed a bit lower to undershoot it. I stuck with this approach when it turned out that the averages tended to be comparable. At the end people were guessing quite low, apparently, but I gambled on the same strategy working anyway -- I'd have needed to be more than twice as certain in numbers such as 10-12 than ones such as 20-25, because of the lower bonus payout associated, and I wasn't that certain.It didn't work out but I have no regrets, since I missed out on just 35 or so cents if I were right all three of the last times, in comparison to the 40+ that even two correct guesses out of three would have yielded.     Anyway, fun game, glad to participate. I'd be interested in being emailed similar studies in the future. :)
